omic `unsafe_load` and `unsafe_store!`","user":{"login":"Tokazama","id":13888485,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEzODg4NDg1","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/13888485?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama","html_url":"https://github.com/Tokazama","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Tokazama/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"body":"This provides and interface to `Intrinsics.atomic_pointerref` and `Intrinsics.atomic_pointerset` through `unsafe_load` and `unsafe_store!`, respectively. The argument structure is similar to atomic field accessors where the fully specified call is `unsafe_load(ptr, i, order)` but since we are dealing with pointers theres also the option to not offset it, `unsafe_load(ptr, order)`.

The corresponding intrinsic methods don't provide an option to move to the ith address of the pointer so I just looked at what the C code for `pointerref` was doing there and imitated it in Julia, but it would be nice to have someone double check that.

